I was his TA at Cambridge.

03:22.900 --> 03:25.619
He was insufferable
even then.

03:28.800 --> 03:31.860
- Have you
read his books?

03:31.910 --> 03:34.401
(whispering): They're terrible.

03:34.440 --> 03:36.579
You know they're terrible,
you're just too polite to say.

03:36.610 --> 03:38.976
Blink if you agree.

03:39.010 --> 03:42.480
See?

03:42.520 --> 03:44.385
That doesn't stop him
squatting over his keyboard

03:44.420 --> 03:46.650
and depositing a fresh one
every six to eight months.

03:46.690 --> 03:49.784
It takes me six to eight
months to write one line.

03:49.830 --> 03:51.957
- Why?

03:51.990 --> 03:54.254
- Poetry is hard.

03:54.300 --> 03:57.326
Too hard for Roman.
Well, it's easier for him

03:57.370 --> 03:59.338
to slide into academia and
dissect the work of others

03:59.370 --> 04:01.395
than it is to stand
by his own words.

04:01.440 --> 04:03.806
- One can appreciate
another's words

04:03.840 --> 04:06.900
without dissecting them.

04:06.940 --> 04:10.478
Though, on occasion, dissection
is the only thing that will do.

04:10.510 --> 04:11.943
(glass shattering)

04:35.100 --> 04:38.558
- Bonsoir.

04:40.580 --> 04:42.571
- Bonsoir.

04:47.020 --> 04:48.817
(engine starting)

05:06.400 --> 05:08.891
Bonsoir?

05:08.940 --> 05:12.376
- Bonsoir.

